===Dual spaces===
The [[Continuous dual|dual space]] (the Banach space of all continuous linear functionals) of {{math|''L&lt;sup&gt;p&lt;/sup&gt;''(''μ'')}} for {{math|1 &lt; ''p'' &lt; ∞}} has a natural isomorphism with {{math|''L&lt;sup&gt;q&lt;/sup&gt;''(''μ'')}}, where {{mvar|q}} is such that {{math|&amp;thinsp;{{sfrac|1|''p''}} + {{sfrac|1|''q''}} {{=}} 1}} (i.e. {{math|1=''q'' = {{sfrac|''p''|''p'' − 1}}}}). This isomorphism associates {{math|''g'' ∈ ''L&lt;sup&gt;q&lt;/sup&gt;''(''μ'')}} with the functional {{math|''κ&lt;sub&gt;p&lt;/sub&gt;''(''g'') ∈ ''L&lt;sup&gt;p&lt;/sup&gt;''(''μ'')&lt;sup&gt;∗&lt;/sup&gt;}} defined by

:&lt;math&gt;f  \mapsto \kappa_p(g)(f)=\int f g \, \mathrm{d}\mu\ \ &lt;/math&gt; for every &lt;math&gt;f \in L^p(\mu)&lt;/math&gt;

The fact that {{math|''κ&lt;sub&gt;p&lt;/sub&gt;''(''g'')}} is well defined and continuous follows from [[Hölder's inequality]]. {{math|''κ&lt;sub&gt;p&lt;/sub&gt;'' : ''L&lt;sup&gt;q&lt;/sup&gt;''(''μ'') → ''L&lt;sup&gt;p&lt;/sup&gt;''(''μ'')&lt;sup&gt;∗&lt;/sup&gt;}} is a linear mapping which is an [[isometry]] by the [[Hölder's inequality#Extremal equality|extremal case]] of Hölder's inequality. It is also possible to show (for example with the [[Radon–Nikodym theorem]], see&lt;ref&gt;{{Citation | last1=Rudin | first1=Walter | author1-link=Walter Rudin | title=Real and Complex Analysis | publisher=Tata McGraw-Hill | location=New Delhi | edition=2nd | year=1980 |isbn=9780070542341}}, Theorem 6.16&lt;/ref&gt;) that any {{math|''G'' ∈ ''L&lt;sup&gt;p&lt;/sup&gt;''(''μ'')&lt;sup&gt;∗&lt;/sup&gt;}} can be expressed this way: i.e., that {{math|''κ&lt;sub&gt;p&lt;/sub&gt;''}} is ''onto''. Since {{math|''κ&lt;sub&gt;p&lt;/sub&gt;''}} is onto and isometric, it is an [[isomorphism]] of [[Banach space]]s. With this (isometric) isomorphism in mind, it is usual to say simply that {{math|''L&lt;sup&gt;q&lt;/sup&gt;''}}  is the dual Banach space of {{math|''L&lt;sup&gt;p&lt;/sup&gt;''}}.

For {{math|1 &lt; ''p'' &lt; ∞}}, the space {{math|''L&lt;sup&gt;p&lt;/sup&gt;''(''μ'')}} is [[reflexive space|reflexive]]. Let {{math|''κ&lt;sub&gt;p&lt;/sub&gt;''}} be as above and let {{math|''κ&lt;sub&gt;q&lt;/sub&gt;'' : ''L&lt;sup&gt;p&lt;/sup&gt;''(''μ'') → ''L&lt;sup&gt;q&lt;/sup&gt;''(''μ'')&lt;sup&gt;∗&lt;/sup&gt;}} be the corresponding linear isometry. Consider the map from {{math|''L&lt;sup&gt;p&lt;/sup&gt;''(''μ'')}} to {{math|''L&lt;sup&gt;p&lt;/sup&gt;''(''μ'')&lt;sup&gt;∗∗&lt;/sup&gt;}}, obtained by composing {{math|''κ&lt;sub&gt;q&lt;/sub&gt;''}} with the [[dual space#Transpose of a continuous linear map|transpose]] (or adjoint) of the inverse of {{math|''κ&lt;sub&gt;p&lt;/sub&gt;''}}:

:&lt;math&gt;j_p : L^p(\mu) \overset{\kappa_q}{\longrightarrow} L^q(\mu)^* \overset{\left(\kappa_p^{-1}\right)^*}{\longrightarrow} L^p(\mu)^{**}&lt;/math&gt;

This map coincides with the [[Reflexive space#Definitions|canonical embedding]] {{mvar|J}} of {{math|''L&lt;sup&gt;p&lt;/sup&gt;''(''μ'')}} into its bidual. Moreover, the map {{math|''j&lt;sub&gt;p&lt;/sub&gt;''}} is onto, as composition of two onto isometries, and this proves reflexivity.

If the measure {{mvar|μ}} on {{mvar|S}} is [[sigma-finite]], then the dual of {{math|''L''&lt;sup&gt;1&lt;/sup&gt;(''μ'')}} is isometrically isomorphic to {{math|''L''&lt;sup&gt;∞&lt;/sup&gt;(''μ'')}} (more precisely, the map {{math|''κ''&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt;}} corresponding to {{math|''p'' {{=}} 1}} is an isometry from {{math|''L''&lt;sup&gt;∞&lt;/sup&gt;(''μ'')}} onto {{math|''L''&lt;sup&gt;1&lt;/sup&gt;(''μ'')&lt;sup&gt;∗&lt;/sup&gt;}}).

The dual of {{math|''L''&lt;sup&gt;∞&lt;/sup&gt;}} is subtler. Elements of {{math|''L''&lt;sup&gt;∞&lt;/sup&gt;(''μ'')&lt;sup&gt;∗&lt;/sup&gt;}} can be identified with bounded signed ''finitely'' additive measures on {{mvar|S}} that are [[absolutely continuous]] with respect to {{mvar|μ}}. See [[ba space]] for more details. If we assume the axiom of choice, this space is much bigger than {{math|''L''&lt;sup&gt;1&lt;/sup&gt;(''μ'')}} except in some trivial cases. However, [[Saharon Shelah]] proved that there are relatively consistent extensions of [[Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory]] (ZF + [[Axiom of dependent choice|DC]] + &quot;Every subset of the real numbers has the [[Baire property]]&quot;) in which the dual of {{math|''ℓ''&lt;sup&gt;∞&lt;/sup&gt;}} is {{math|''ℓ''&lt;sup&gt;1&lt;/sup&gt;}}.&lt;ref&gt;{{Citation|title=Handbook of Analysis and its Foundations|last=Schechter |first=Eric|year=1997| publisher=Academic Press Inc.|location=London}} See Sections 14.77 and 27.44–47&lt;/ref&gt;

===Embeddings===
Colloquially, if {{math|1 ≤ ''p'' &lt; ''q'' ≤ ∞}}, then {{math|''L&lt;sup&gt;p&lt;/sup&gt;''(''S'', ''μ'')}} contains functions that are more locally singular, while elements of {{math|''L&lt;sup&gt;q&lt;/sup&gt;''(''S'', ''μ'')}} can be more spread out. Consider the Lebesgue measure on the half line {{math|(0, ∞)}}. A continuous function in {{math|''L''&lt;sup&gt;1&lt;/sup&gt;}} might blow up near {{math|0}} but must decay sufficiently fast toward infinity. On the other hand, continuous functions in {{math|''L''&lt;sup&gt;∞&lt;/sup&gt;}} need not decay at all but no blow-up is allowed. The precise technical result is the following.&lt;ref name=&quot;VillaniEmbeddings&quot;&gt;{{Citation|title=Another note on the inclusion {{math|''L&lt;sup&gt;p&lt;/sup&gt;''(''μ'') ⊂ ''L&lt;sup&gt;q&lt;/sup&gt;''(''μ'')}}|last=Villani |first=Alfonso|year=1985| journal=Amer. Math. Monthly|volume=92 |number=7 |pages=485–487 |doi=10.2307/2322503 |mr=801221|jstor=2322503 }}&lt;/ref&gt; Suppose that {{math|0 &lt; ''p'' &lt; ''q'' ≤ ∞}}. Then:

#{{math|''L&lt;sup&gt;q&lt;/sup&gt;''(''S'', ''μ'') ⊂ ''L&lt;sup&gt;p&lt;/sup&gt;''(''S'', ''μ'')}} iff {{mvar|S}} does not contain sets of finite but arbitrarily large measure, and
#{{math|''L&lt;sup&gt;p&lt;/sup&gt;''(''S'', ''μ'') ⊂ ''L&lt;sup&gt;q&lt;/sup&gt;''(''S'', ''μ'')}} iff {{mvar|S}} does not contain sets of non-zero but arbitrarily small measure.

Neither condition holds for the real line with the Lebesgue measure. In both cases the embedding is continuous, in that the identity operator is a bounded linear map from
{{math|''L&lt;sup&gt;q&lt;/sup&gt;''}} to {{math|''L&lt;sup&gt;p&lt;/sup&gt;''}} in the first case,
and {{math|''L&lt;sup&gt;p&lt;/sup&gt;''}} to {{math|''L&lt;sup&gt;q&lt;/sup&gt;''}} in the second.
(This is a consequence of the [[closed graph theorem]]
and properties of {{math|''L&lt;sup&gt;p&lt;/sup&gt;''}} spaces.) Indeed, if the domain {{mvar|S}} has finite measure,
one can make the following explicit calculation using [[Hölder's inequality]]

:&lt;math&gt;\ \|\mathbf{1}f^{p}\|_1 \le \|\mathbf{1}\|_{q/(q-p)} \|f^{p}\|_{q/p} &lt;/math&gt;
leading to
:&lt;math&gt;\ \|f\|_p \le \mu(S)^{1/p - 1/q} \|f\|_q &lt;/math&gt;.

The constant appearing in the above inequality is optimal, in the sense that the [[operator norm]] of the identity {{math|''I'' : ''L&lt;sup&gt;q&lt;/sup&gt;''(''S'', ''μ'') → ''L&lt;sup&gt;p&lt;/sup&gt;''(''S'', ''μ'')}} is precisely

:&lt;math&gt;\|I\|_{q,p} = \mu(S)^{1/p - 1/q}&lt;/math&gt;

the case of equality being achieved exactly when {{math|&amp;thinsp;''f''&amp;thinsp; {{=}} 1}} {{mvar|μ}}-a.e.

===Dense subspaces===
Throughout this section we assume that: {{math|1 ≤ ''p'' &lt; ∞}}.

Let {{math|(''S'', Σ, ''μ'')}} be a measure space. An ''integrable simple function'' {{math|&amp;thinsp;''f''&amp;thinsp;}} on {{mvar|S}} is one of the form

:&lt;math&gt;f = \sum_{j=1}^n a_j \mathbf{1}_{A_j}&lt;/math&gt;

where {{math|''a&lt;sub&gt;j&lt;/sub&gt;''}} is scalar, {{math|''A&lt;sub&gt;j&lt;/sub&gt;'' ∈ Σ}} has finite measure and &lt;math&gt;{\mathbf 1}_{A_j}&lt;/math&gt; is the [[indicator function]] of the set &lt;math&gt;A_j&lt;/math&gt;, for {{math|''j'' {{=}} 1, ..., ''n''}}. By construction of the [[Lebesgue integration|integral]], the vector space of integrable simple functions is dense in {{math|''L&lt;sup&gt;p&lt;/sup&gt;''(''S'', Σ, ''μ'')}}.

More can be said when {{mvar|S}} is a [[Normal space|normal]] [[topological space]] and {{math|Σ}} its [[Borel algebra|Borel {{mvar|σ}}&amp;ndash;algebra]], i.e., the smallest {{mvar|σ}}&amp;ndash;algebra of subsets of {{mvar|S}} containing the [[open set]]s.

Suppose {{math|''V'' ⊂ ''S''}} is an open set with {{math|''μ''(''V'') &lt; ∞}}. It can be proved that for every Borel set {{math|''A'' ∈ Σ}} contained in {{mvar|V}}, and for every {{math|''ε'' &gt; 0}}, there exist a closed set {{mvar|F}} and an open set {{mvar|U}} such that

:&lt;math&gt;F \subset A \subset U \subset V \quad \text{and} \quad \mu(U) - \mu(F) = \mu(U \setminus F) &lt; \varepsilon&lt;/math&gt;

It follows that there exists a continuous [[Urysohn's lemma#Formal statement | Urysohn function]] {{math|0 ≤ ''&amp;phi;'' ≤ 1}} on {{math|''S''}} that is {{math|1}} on {{math|''F''}} and {{math|0}} on {{math|''S'' ∖ ''U''}}, with

:&lt;math&gt;\int_S |\mathbf{1}_A - \varphi| \, \mathrm{d}\mu &lt; \varepsilon \ .&lt;/math&gt;

If {{mvar|S}} can be covered by an increasing sequence {{math|(''V&lt;sub&gt;n&lt;/sub&gt;'')}} of open sets that have finite measure, then the space of {{mvar|p}}&amp;ndash;integrable continuous functions is dense in {{math|''L&lt;sup&gt;p&lt;/sup&gt;''(''S'', Σ, ''μ'')}}. More precisely, one can use bounded continuous functions that vanish outside one of the open sets {{math|''V&lt;sub&gt;n&lt;/sub&gt;''}}.

This applies in particular when {{math|''S'' {{=}} '''R'''&lt;sup&gt;''d''&lt;/sup&gt;}} and when {{mvar|μ}} is the Lebesgue measure. The space of continuous and compactly supported functions is dense in {{math|''L&lt;sup&gt;p&lt;/sup&gt;''('''R'''&lt;sup&gt;''d''&lt;/sup&gt;)}}. Similarly, the space of integrable ''step functions'' is dense in {{math|''L&lt;sup&gt;p&lt;/sup&gt;''('''R'''&lt;sup&gt;''d''&lt;/sup&gt;)}}; this space is the linear span of indicator functions of bounded intervals when {{math|''d'' {{=}} 1}}, of bounded rectangles when {{math|''d'' {{=}} 2}} and more generally of products of bounded intervals.

Several properties of general functions in {{math|''L&lt;sup&gt;p&lt;/sup&gt;''('''R'''&lt;sup&gt;''d''&lt;/sup&gt;)}} are first proved for continuous and compactly supported functions (sometimes for step functions), then extended by density to all functions. For example, it is proved this way that translations are continuous on {{math|''L&lt;sup&gt;p&lt;/sup&gt;''('''R'''&lt;sup&gt;''d''&lt;/sup&gt;)}}, in the following sense:

:&lt;math&gt;\forall f \in L^p (\mathbf{R}^d): \qquad \left \|\tau_t f - f \right \|_p \to 0, \quad \text{ as } \mathbf{R}^d \ni t \to 0,&lt;/math&gt;

where
 
:&lt;math&gt; (\tau_t f)(x) = f(x - t).&lt;/math&gt;

=={{math|''L&lt;sup&gt;p&lt;/sup&gt;'' (0 &lt; ''p'' &lt; 1)}}==
Let {{math|(''S'', Σ, ''μ'')}} be a measure space. If {{math|0 &lt; ''p'' &lt; 1}}, then {{math|''L&lt;sup&gt;p&lt;/sup&gt;''(''μ'')}} can be defined as above: it is the vector space of those measurable functions {{math|&amp;thinsp;''f''&amp;thinsp;}} such that

:&lt;math&gt;N_p(f) = \int_S |f|^p\, d\mu &lt; \infty.&lt;/math&gt;

As before, we may introduce the {{mvar|p}}-norm {{math|{{!!}}&amp;thinsp;''f''&amp;thinsp;{{!!}}&lt;sub&gt;''p''&lt;/sub&gt; {{=}} ''N&lt;sub&gt;p&lt;/sub&gt;''(&amp;thinsp;''f''&amp;thinsp;)&lt;sup&gt;1/''p''&lt;/sup&gt;}}, but {{math|{{!!}} · {{!!}}&lt;sub&gt;''p''&lt;/sub&gt;}} does not satisfy the triangle inequality in this case, and defines only a [[quasi-norm]].  The inequality {{math|(''a'' + ''b'')&lt;sup&gt;&amp;thinsp;''p''&lt;/sup&gt; ≤ ''a&lt;sup&gt;&amp;thinsp;p&lt;/sup&gt;'' + ''b&lt;sup&gt;&amp;thinsp;p&lt;/sup&gt;''}}, valid for {{math|''a'', ''b'' ≥ 0}} implies that {{harv|Rudin|1991|loc=§1.47}}

:&lt;math&gt;N_p(f+g)\le N_p(f) + N_p(g)&lt;/math&gt;

and so the function

:&lt;math&gt;d_p(f,g) = N_p(f-g) = \|f - g\|_p^p&lt;/math&gt;

is a metric on {{math|''L&lt;sup&gt;p&lt;/sup&gt;''(''μ'')}}. The resulting metric space is [[complete space|complete]]; the verification is similar to the familiar case when {{math|''p'' ≥ 1}}.

In this setting {{math|''L&lt;sup&gt;p&lt;/sup&gt;''}} satisfies a ''reverse Minkowski inequality'', that is for {{math|''u'', ''v''}} in {{math|''L&lt;sup&gt;p&lt;/sup&gt;''}}

:&lt;math&gt; \||u|+|v|\|_p\geq \|u\|_p+\|v\|_p&lt;/math&gt;

This result may be used to prove [[Clarkson's inequalities]], which are in turn used to establish the [[uniformly convex space|uniform convexity]] of the spaces {{math|''L&lt;sup&gt;p&lt;/sup&gt;''}} for {{math|1 &lt; ''p'' &lt; ∞}} {{harv|Adams|Fournier|2003}}.

The space {{math|''L&lt;sup&gt;p&lt;/sup&gt;''}} for {{math|0 &lt; ''p'' &lt; 1}} is an [[F-space]]: it admits a complete translation-invariant metric with respect to which the vector space operations are continuous. It is also [[locally bounded]], much like the case {{math|''p'' ≥ 1}}. It is the prototypical example of an [[F-space]] that, for most reasonable measure spaces, is not [[locally convex]]: in {{math|''ℓ&lt;sup&gt;&amp;thinsp;p&lt;/sup&gt;''}} or {{math|''L&lt;sup&gt;p&lt;/sup&gt;''([0, 1])}}, every open convex set containing the {{math|0}} function is unbounded for the {{mvar|p}}-quasi-norm; therefore, the {{math|0}} vector does not possess a fundamental system of convex neighborhoods. Specifically, this is true if the measure space {{mvar|S}} contains an infinite family of disjoint measurable sets of finite positive measure.

The only nonempty convex open set in {{math|''L&lt;sup&gt;p&lt;/sup&gt;''([0, 1])}} is the entire space {{harv|Rudin|1991|loc=§1.47}}. As a particular consequence, there are no nonzero linear functionals on {{math|''L&lt;sup&gt;p&lt;/sup&gt;''([0, 1])}}: the dual space is the zero space. In the case of the [[counting measure]] on the natural numbers (producing the sequence space {{math|''L&lt;sup&gt;p&lt;/sup&gt;''(''μ'') {{=}} ''ℓ&lt;sup&gt;&amp;thinsp;p&lt;/sup&gt;''}}), the bounded linear functionals on {{math|''ℓ&lt;sup&gt;&amp;thinsp;p&lt;/sup&gt;''}} are exactly those that are bounded on {{math|''ℓ''&lt;sup&gt;&amp;thinsp;1&lt;/sup&gt;}}, namely those given by sequences in {{math|''ℓ''&lt;sup&gt;&amp;thinsp;∞&lt;/sup&gt;}}. Although {{math|''ℓ&lt;sup&gt;&amp;thinsp;p&lt;/sup&gt;''}} does contain non-trivial convex open sets, it fails to have enough of them to give a base for the topology.

The situation of having no linear functionals is highly undesirable for the purposes of doing analysis. In the case of the Lebesgue measure on {{math|'''R'''&lt;sup&gt;''n''&lt;/sup&gt;}}, rather than work with {{math|''L&lt;sup&gt;p&lt;/sup&gt;''}} for {{math|0 &lt; ''p'' &lt; 1}}, it is common to work with the [[Hardy space]] {{math|''H&lt;sup&gt;&amp;thinsp;p&lt;/sup&gt;''}} whenever possible, as this has quite a few linear functionals: enough to distinguish points from one another. However, the [[Hahn–Banach theorem]] still fails in {{math|''H&lt;sup&gt;&amp;thinsp;p&lt;/sup&gt;''}} for {{math|''p'' &lt; 1}} {{harv|Duren|1970|loc=§7.5}}.

==={{math|''L''&lt;sup&gt;0&lt;/sup&gt;}}, the space of measurable functions===
The vector space of (equivalence classes of) measurable functions on {{math|(''S'', Σ, ''μ'')}} is denoted {{math|''L''&lt;sup&gt;0&lt;/sup&gt;(''S'', Σ, ''μ'')}} {{harv|Kalton|Peck|Roberts|1984}}. By definition, it contains all the {{math|''L&lt;sup&gt;p&lt;/sup&gt;''}}, and is equipped with the topology of ''[[convergence in measure]]''. When {{mvar|μ}} is a probability measure (i.e., {{math|''μ''(''S'') {{=}} 1}}), this mode of convergence is named ''[[convergence in probability]]''.

The description is easier when {{mvar|μ}} is finite. If {{mvar|μ}} is a finite measure on {{math|(''S'', Σ)}}, the {{math|0}} function admits for the convergence in measure the following fundamental system of neighborhoods

:&lt;math&gt;V_\varepsilon = \Bigl\{ f : \mu \bigl(\{x : |f(x)| &gt; \varepsilon \} \bigr) &lt; \varepsilon \Bigr\}, \qquad \varepsilon &gt; 0&lt;/math&gt;

The topology can be defined by any metric {{mvar|d}} of the form

:&lt;math&gt;d(f, g) = \int_S \varphi \bigl( |f(x) - g(x)| \bigr) \, \mathrm{d}\mu(x)&lt;/math&gt;

where {{mvar|φ}} is bounded continuous concave and non-decreasing on {{math|[0, ∞)}}, with {{math|''φ''(0) {{=}} 0}} and {{math|''φ''(''t'') &gt; 0}} when {{math|''t'' &gt; 0}} (for example, {{math|''φ''(''t'') {{=}} min(''t'', 1))}}. Such a metric is called [[Paul Lévy (mathematician)|Lévy]]-metric for {{math|''L''&lt;sup&gt;0&lt;/sup&gt;}}. Under this metric the space {{math|''L''&lt;sup&gt;0&lt;/sup&gt;}} is complete (it is again an F-space). The space {{math|''L''&lt;sup&gt;0&lt;/sup&gt;}} is in general not locally bounded, and not locally convex.

For the infinite Lebesgue measure {{mvar|λ}} on {{math|'''R'''&lt;sup&gt;''n''&lt;/sup&gt;}}, the definition of the fundamental system of neighborhoods could be modified as follows

:&lt;math&gt;W_\varepsilon = \left\{ f : \lambda \left(\left\{ x : |f(x)| &gt; \varepsilon \text{ and } |x| &lt; \frac{1}{\varepsilon}\right\} \right) &lt; \varepsilon \right\}&lt;/math&gt;
